I currently run for Utah State University and helped my team qualify for the 2021 NCAA cross country championships for the second time in school history. - In the spring of 2023 I will graduate with two bachelor degrees, one in Psychology and one in Sociology, and an associate’s degree in Criminal Justice. athletes.Biography: Hello! My name is Lauren and I play division 1 rugby for Grand Canyon University. At GCU I am studying marketing and advertising. Besides this, I am also a student worker here! I prioritize my diet and my health habits and am always striving to be better in all ways. Leadership is something that I absolutely love and has always came naturally to me. I have suffered an ongoing knee injury for 3 years now. I have battled back from 2 knee surgeries and now a 3rd partial tear knowing that I eventually am going to have a story worth sharing. This year I am looking forward to finally sharing and showing my story that I have worked so hard for and been so patient with. ONLY GOD 🙏🏼

athletes.Name: Leah Kennedy
athletes.Biography: My name is Leah Kennedy, and I am a Pre-Med Major with a Dance Minor. I am an upcoming junior at Troy University. I aspire to become a Cardiothoracic surgeon in the future. - - I’ve been throwing all my life. On my mothers side of the family, track runs in our blood. My mother was a hurdler/jumper, my aunt was a heptathlete, and my uncle was a sprinter. My grandfather was also very involved in track while he was in the Airforce and when he was younger. Track is my life. I took to throwing because I struggled with self image when I was a kid. Now, I throw to because it keeps me sane. athletes.Name: Amaya De La Cruz
athletes.Biography: Cheerleader to rugby player. Talk about a complete 180°! My name is Amaya De La Cruz, and I am a part of the D1 Women’s Rugby Program at Grand Canyon University. I am studying Communications with an Emphasis in Broadcasting and New Media, along with a Minor in Pre-Law. Most of my childhood was spent on the sidelines cheering on teams to achieve that victory. However, I knew deep down I wasn’t supposed to be the one watching, but the one WINNING. I traded in my cheer bow for a mouth guard, and my life has completely changed. Rugby is more than the gnarly bruises and the padless tackling, but it is about grit, togetherness, and sacrificial love. Being a girl in this growing sport, I am so encouraged by the amazing women around me to take pride in my strength and find beauty in my muscles. Rugby is so special because no matter the body shape, speed, or ability, everyone has a purpose on the pitch. This sport has taught me so much, and I hope to spread the rugby awareness around the U.S.

athletes.Name: Nicholas Stacey
athletes.Biography: Hi everyone my name is Nicholas Stacey but most people call me Nick or Stacey for short. I’m a student-athlete for the University of the Cumberlands. I’m an education major with emphasis in special education and mathematics. I play football and I am an inside linebacker. My hobbies include video games, hanging with family, and also playing pickup soccer with friends on the side. I also enjoy working out and training young student-athletes on the side. - My backstory includes a lot of adversity throughout my personal life. I was born with a cleft lip and pallet and from a young age was having surgeries left and right to fix those issues. I was told I could never play football because my surgeries would interfere with the seasons. I was able to recover fast and stronger then before and made myself able to play through those hardships. I didn’t allow the adversity to control my life. I hope to coach and instill those same values in my athletes in the future.

athletes.Biography: From the time I was young I always looked up to my cousin. He was a great football player and an even better wrestler. When I had lost my last high school wrestling match I was at my lowest. However, I was able to pick myself back up and lace up my shoes one more time. I decided to wrestle in college and became a starter as a true freshman at the University of Central Missouri. I'm still fairly inexperienced but I learn every day and continue to improve until no one can beat me, and I stand at the top of the national stage. I also have a growing YouTube channel that I upload on consistently. I wasn't supposed to be here right now, yet here I am, unapologetically me. - - https://kxeo.com/2021/03/15/mexico-high-school-grappler-terrell-williams-signs-national-letter-of-intent-to-wrestle-at-university-of-central-missouri/

athletes.Name: Davion Robinson
athletes.Biography: Davion Robinson is a collegiate basketball player at The Evergreen State College in Olympia, WA and is a social media influencer as well. Robinson recently majored in Sports Management at the University of Antelope Valley in Lancaster, CA the past few years and once transferred switched his major program to Business Management and Entrepreneurship. In an era of individuals that is determined to become self-made, Robinson has valued his freedom of creativity, content creation and performance in which has enabled him to grow a supportive platform of followers (270k+ on Instagram) that impacts his NIL value massively. Although Robinson is currently an NAIA college athlete, he is still able to remain top 10 on most NIL evaluation lists that rank him amongst some of the biggest names in the country receiving mainstream commercial attention. The balance of fashion, lifestyle and athletics is what keeps the following of Robinson propelling and he prides himself on “remaining authentic”.

At Oklahoma, we strive for greatness. OU gymnasts are some of the most dedicated and hard-working people you will find in the realm of collegiate sports. We strive to be the best, which is why I am looking for brands that will help myself and my team on this journey to become national champions! Outside of gymnastics, I am passionate about filmmaking. I spend a lot of my time creating impact through my video and photo skills. I have worked with both the University of Minnesota and Oklahoma’s athletic department specifically with gymnastics related content. Just recently, I helped complete a documentary about the decline of men’s gymnastics. I hope that your brand will shed light on our sport!

athletes.Biography: I am a 5th year Texas and Team USA rower! My international racing experience includes two under 19 national teams in 2017 and 2018 including a bronze medal in the coxed four in 2018. I also represented the US in a pair at the Youth Olympics in 2018. Most recently I won a gold medal in the 2022 Under 23 World Championships. This year I was nominated for the NCAA Woman of the Year award and named the US Rowing under 23 Athlete of the Year. In my free time I enjoy baking, drawing, spending time with teammates, and helping my dad with our family business in Austin. My goal following my career at Texas is to make the 2024 Olympic team!

athletes.Name: Andrew Petrowski
athletes.Biography: My name is Andrew Petrowski. I'm a junior at Baylor University and I play baseball. Before transferring to Baylor, I attended two junior colleges, Garden City Community College and San Jacinto College. In the coming years, I plan on playing professional baseball and getting my degree in finance. My dream is to play professionally and I won't stop until I achieve that. Last year at San Jacinto we made it to the Junior College World Series, and playing in front of that crowd and seeing the impact we had on all the fans truly reinforced my motivation to play in the MLB. While at San Jacinto we held multiple Special Needs days in which children from all over the city came to play baseball and have fun. This was a huge eye opener to me about the importance of sports and the impact I can have on children's lives. Seeing their faces light up and their problems seemingly vanish for a couple of hours engraved a lasting memory in my heart that I will never forget.

athletes.Name: Shawn Toney
athletes.Biography: To be… or not? It’s more a prying anxiety than a question. Nonetheless, Hamlet thought it meaningful enough to ask. It’s one of the strangest “verbs” I’ve come across, and I have a hard time wrapping my head around the fact that it even is one. This verb has become more than just a word to analyze through Sparknotes. It’s become the greatest and perhaps most insurmountable skill I’ve learned: to be; or, rather, the “will to being.”- I’ve come to call any obstacles in my career a “will to being” as I believe that to truly “be” or “exist” in life means to surrender comfort. I could have learned isolated hurdling instead of picking up the discus—a sport unfit for my body frame of 6’1. I’d be blind to the harshness of reality and see nothing but infinite bliss. But, it would be meaningless. - I’m fortunate to have won many battles. Yet, I’m more than the result, I am the struggle that comes with it. Without obstacles, my journeys would be colorless. Without the will to being, I would not be.

athletes.Name: Ethan Coombes
athletes.Biography: I’m a baseball player at Texas Tech University and have had a long journey to get where I am today. During the process I have learned a lot about being a good teammate and a good representative of the community. I started my career at a small division 2 in New Mexico, before transferring to Howard College due to covid complications in the state. From here I earned an opportunity to play at Lubbock Christian University for a year and finish my bachelors degree in business administration. With a year left of eligibility, I wanted to pursue something that would push me to my limits. Texas Tech reached out and I couldn’t be more excited to represent the Red Raider baseball team and help this team get back to Omaha. Now as a graduate student pursuing a sports management degree, I will spend more time contributing to this community and teaching the youth about the game of baseball. As an athlete, it is my responsibility to show young players how great this game is, and to always dream big.
athletes.Afiliations: Texas Tech Red Raiders, Lubbock Christian University, Eastern New Mexico University, Howard College ,  Big 12,

athletes.Biography: First generation college student. I’ve been playing golf since I was 4 years old, and competitively since I was 6. Nationally include; https://www.ajga.org/ , https://www.drivechipandputt.com/ , https://www.uskidsgolf.com/ , https://www.pgajrleague.com/ Locally include; https://gspga.com/ , and what I am most proud of is my membership and volunteerism with the https://www.kellygibsonfoundation.org/ Their organization is changing the game of golf for juniors all across the Southeast United State. Their mentorship program is the best of its kind having junior tour players 13 and older mentoring for the 7-12 year olds in their nine hole round. The mentors are then eligible for scholarship money at the end of the summer based on their academics and volunteerism that can further their education, regardless of their golfing abilities. I am honored to be a small part in the tremendous work they are doing for the game.

athletes.Name: Lila Splavec
athletes.Biography: My name is Lila Splavec, I’m a student athlete at Siena Heights University currently competing on the womens volleyball team. My journey to becoming a student athlete has been anything but typical, and I’m not just talking about navigating life as a 6’4” female! I’ve battled back from injuries, taken breaks from my training to prioritize my mental health and learned a ton about myself along the way. I’m excited for any and all of the opportunities that come my way to share my story and encourage others to advocate for themselves and take up the space they deserve to become the best student athlete possible!

athletes.Name: Abby Bond
athletes.Biography: My name is Abby Bond and I am a collegiate student-athlete attending Corban University in Salem, OR. I am an 18 year old beach volleyball player who competes against many different athletes across the West Coast. I enjoy traveling, working out, watching movies, hiking, and spending time with my family in my free time. I’ve always been a super adventurous and creative person and I enjoy learning new things. I am also an advocate for people struggling with disabilities and for young athletes looking to pursue the next level of competition. I myself have a very uncommon genetic disability called hypokalemic periodic paralysis that has always been a part of my life. I want to encourage young athletes to pursue their dreams and teach them to not let their circumstances deter them from doing what they love.

athletes.Biography: I'm a sophomore majoring in Kinesiology, pursing a career in sports medicine, on University of Wyoming Women's Cross Country & Indoor/ Outdoor Track team. On the track I run the 3k & 5k. I have made UW top 10 All times in the 3k & 5k. I am very passionate in my trail running I have competed in many races over the years, one of my biggest races I've competed in was the 2019 Pikes Peak Ascent for the 1st time (1st in age group) definitely my favorite race so far. Any chance I get I will be out on the trail or in the mountains, chasing after my dreams. I hope to again compete in the Pikes Peak Ascent & marathon as well as many more trail and sky races! - In my free time you will find me outside with my family and friends exploring new places, Mtn. Biking, training horses, team roping, breakaway roping & many more outdoor activities. The most important thing to me is my Family & Friends, if it wasn't for them I wouldn't be where I am today with out their help, support and encouragement.

athletes.Name: Abigail Whitman
athletes.Sport: Cross Country, Women's Track and Field
athletes.Biography: My name is Abigail Whitman, and I was born and raised in the cowboy town of Laramie, Wyoming. I am double majoring in Accounting and Outdoor Recreation and Tourism and Management. I am excited to be #7 in the indoor 5k and #5 in the outdoor 10k of UW all time. I am honored to be running the 5k and 10k on the University of Wyoming team.- Besides running, I like to be in the outdoors whenever I can while spending it with family and friends. I enjoy climbing, summiting mountains, paddleboarding, cross country skiing, downhill skiing, trail running, and much more. Some big accomplishments I have done with these activities are summiting the Grand Teton and Teewinot in the Teton Range, hiking 14ers in Colorado, pushing grades on climbing routes, and pushing myself through challenging physical and mental moments. I am grateful to be surrounded by my teammates and friends that all push me to become a better person in running, as a student, and in my day-to-day life.
